WEBVTT

00:02.380 --> 00:04.580
I can't believe this window
is still stuck.

00:04.580 --> 00:05.670
I'm freezing
to death!

00:05.670 --> 00:07.380
Before you die,

00:07.380 --> 00:09.170
where in your room did you hide
your Halloween candy?

00:09.170 --> 00:10.540
Mom,
I didn't think any car

00:10.540 --> 00:11.580
could be worse
than your minivan.

00:11.580 --> 00:12.880
But here we are.

00:12.880 --> 00:14.790
Kindly address all complaints
to your father.

00:14.790 --> 00:16.210
He's the one
who's been driving around

00:16.210 --> 00:18.210
with that broken window
for two years.

00:18.210 --> 00:19.580
I'm pretending
I'm Shackleton

00:19.580 --> 00:21.500
when his boat got stuck
in the ice.

00:21.500 --> 00:22.670
I'm pretending
I was switched at birth

00:22.670 --> 00:24.170
and my real family
is waiting at school

00:24.170 --> 00:26.040
to whisk me back
to our castle.

00:26.040 --> 00:28.210
[ Exhales ]

00:28.210 --> 00:29.830
♪♪

00:29.830 --> 00:33.290
[ Brakes squeal ]

00:33.290 --> 00:34.580
Okay,
we're here!

00:34.580 --> 00:35.710
Time for you to bother
other grown-ups.

00:35.710 --> 00:36.830
Love you!

00:41.250 --> 00:42.620
Mama,
the door won't open.

00:42.620 --> 00:43.880
♪♪

00:43.880 --> 00:47.460
[ Car horns honking ]

00:47.460 --> 00:48.460
♪♪

00:48.460 --> 00:49.460
It still won't open.

00:49.460 --> 00:51.670
Mine, too!
Oh God, we're trapped!

00:51.670 --> 00:53.620
This is
just like Shackleton.

00:53.620 --> 00:56.210
Pretty soon, we're gonna be
eating the sled dogs.

00:56.210 --> 00:58.120
[ Sighs ]
The electrical is shot.

00:58.120 --> 01:00.000
Maybe I shouldn't have bought
that big subwoofer

01:00.000 --> 01:01.920
from the guy
who bags my groceries.

01:01.920 --> 01:03.250
[ Honking continues ]

01:03.250 --> 01:06.040
Oh, my God, there's the new guy,
Trip Windsor.

01:06.040 --> 01:08.040
All right,
abandon ship.

01:08.040 --> 01:10.580
Everyone, crawl out
of Taylor's window.

01:10.580 --> 01:11.750
No way!

01:11.750 --> 01:12.830
Not in this shirt!

01:12.830 --> 01:14.750
I finally found John Varvatos
at Marshalls.

01:14.750 --> 01:16.000
[ Groans ]

01:16.000 --> 01:17.170
No,
not in front of Trip!

01:17.170 --> 01:18.500
I'll just quit school
and stay here.

01:18.500 --> 01:19.960
Yeah,
she doesn't need school.

01:19.960 --> 01:21.380
Let her
embrace her future.

01:21.380 --> 01:23.120
Take her to the nearest
Lancôme counter.

01:23.120 --> 01:25.080
The longer it takes
for you to crawl,

01:25.080 --> 01:26.920
the longer
people are gonna stare.

01:26.920 --> 01:29.170
To the lifeboats!

01:29.170 --> 01:32.620
♪♪

01:51.290 --> 01:52.580
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

01:52.580 --> 01:54.210
[ Honking continues ]

01:54.210 --> 01:56.620
Thank you for the most
humiliating moment of my life!

01:56.620 --> 01:58.040
Please!

01:58.040 --> 01:59.380
Wait till you hear my speech
at your wedding.

01:59.380 --> 02:00.790
[ Sighs ]

02:00.790 --> 02:01.830
[ Honking continues ]

02:01.830 --> 02:06.540
♪♪

02:06.540 --> 02:09.670
So that is why I am never
driving your car again.

02:09.670 --> 02:11.540
Well, at least you got the doors
to work when you got home.

02:11.540 --> 02:12.670
♪♪

02:12.670 --> 02:14.460
[ Yelling ]

02:14.460 --> 02:16.460
I got birthed
by a sedan today, Greg.

02:16.460 --> 02:17.670
And the OB-GYN?

02:17.670 --> 02:19.420
The neighbor's gardener.

02:19.420 --> 02:21.380
It's time to take your car
to the mechanic

02:21.380 --> 02:22.460
and get it fixed.

02:22.460 --> 02:23.670
I'd love to,

02:23.670 --> 02:25.000
but I just don't think
we can afford to right now.

02:25.000 --> 02:26.250
My book
comes out tomorrow,

02:26.250 --> 02:27.580
and if it doesn't sell,
I'm not getting tenure.

02:27.580 --> 02:29.580
Do you know what happens to
professors who don't get tenure?

02:29.580 --> 02:30.830
Don't spiral.

02:30.830 --> 02:32.500
They end up
substitute teachers

02:32.500 --> 02:34.290
moonlighting as hosts
at the Cheesecake Factory!

02:34.290 --> 02:35.540
I'm gonna gain 15...

02:35.540 --> 02:37.960
like that! Aaand...
you're spiraling.

02:37.960 --> 02:39.710
Why are you
assuming the worst?

02:39.710 --> 02:41.580
It doesn't matter
about the book.

02:41.580 --> 02:43.580
You're gonna get tenure
either way.

02:43.580 --> 02:45.210
Katie,
that's not how it works.

02:45.210 --> 02:47.750
If the book fails, we could
end up in the poor house.

02:47.750 --> 02:49.040
End up?

02:49.040 --> 02:50.830
Not one countertop
in this entire house

02:50.830 --> 02:52.120
is made of granite.

02:52.120 --> 02:53.420
We're already here.

02:53.420 --> 02:55.420
Himalayan salt?

02:55.420 --> 02:57.830
Who are we, Facebook employees
five through nine?

02:57.830 --> 02:59.380
[ Salt container thuds ]

02:59.380 --> 03:00.710
And who's not finishing
their Go-Gurt?

03:00.710 --> 03:02.420
This family
is now on a budget.

03:02.420 --> 03:05.080
New rule --
if you're food, you get eaten.

03:05.080 --> 03:07.540
But what about
Hans Gruber?

03:07.540 --> 03:08.540
He's food!

03:08.540 --> 03:09.960
Are you gonna eat him?!

03:09.960 --> 03:10.710
[ Hans Gruber snorting ]

03:10.710 --> 03:12.120
What? No.

03:12.120 --> 03:13.750
Hans Gruber,
we knew this day would come.

03:13.750 --> 03:15.080
Run!

03:15.080 --> 03:17.120
[ Hans Gruber oinking ]

03:18.460 --> 03:20.620
I'm gonna leave a candle
on my window tonight

03:20.620 --> 03:22.540
so my parents with a castle
can find me.

03:22.540 --> 03:25.540
♪♪

03:32.540 --> 03:33.540
♪♪

03:33.540 --> 03:35.420
Greg's book
comes out today,

03:35.420 --> 03:37.420
and he's worried
nobody's gonna buy it.

03:37.420 --> 03:38.170
I'll buy one.

03:39.330 --> 03:41.380
What? I bet he has
a dreamy author photo

03:41.380 --> 03:42.790
where he's sort of
staring at you

03:42.790 --> 03:45.710
with his glasses dangling
from his pillowy lips.

03:45.710 --> 03:48.080
Doris, you have your own husband
to fantasize about.

03:48.080 --> 03:50.670
All my Richard fantasies involve
me pushing him off a boat.

03:50.670 --> 03:53.670
[ Laughing ]
So, is Greg spiraling?

03:53.670 --> 03:54.960
To save money
on electricity,

03:54.960 --> 03:56.380
he wants us to unplug
the digital clock

03:56.380 --> 03:58.380
and just reset it
every time we get home.

03:58.380 --> 04:00.880
Greg is spiraling. [ Groans
] I need that car fixed.

04:00.880 --> 04:03.000
This morning when the gardener
pulled me through the window,

04:03.000 --> 04:04.830
he got
a big handful of Katie.

04:04.830 --> 04:06.960
Well, maybe Greg's book
will get some positive reviews

04:06.960 --> 04:08.000
and he'll calm down.

04:08.000 --> 04:09.170
Maybe.

04:09.170 --> 04:11.000
Or definitely.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.790
You two are going to
review his book on Amazon.

04:14.790 --> 04:16.080
If there's homework,

04:16.080 --> 04:17.710
I'm gonna stop coming
to these breakfasts.

04:17.710 --> 04:19.500
You don't have to read it --
Just give it a glowing review.

04:19.500 --> 04:21.420
The positive feedback
will make him feel better.

04:21.420 --> 04:23.540
Then he'll relax,
and then we can fix the car.

04:23.540 --> 04:25.000
Do you really think
our two reviews

04:25.000 --> 04:26.380
are gonna make
a difference?

04:26.380 --> 04:28.420
Trust me, one of my favorite
things about Greg

04:28.420 --> 04:31.880
is that a little breeze at
his back blows him a long way.

04:31.880 --> 04:33.170
Merry Christmas,
Greg.

04:33.170 --> 04:34.330
Oh, honey,

04:34.330 --> 04:35.960
you shouldn't spend money
on lottery tickets --

04:35.960 --> 04:38.580
no one ever wins.

04:38.580 --> 04:41.580
Look at that!
I won $10!

04:41.580 --> 04:43.170
Kids, we're going
to Benihana!

04:43.170 --> 04:45.290
Everyone can have sodas!

04:45.290 --> 04:46.460
I went
to Benihana once.

04:46.460 --> 04:48.170
The chef flipped shrimp tails
in the air

04:48.170 --> 04:49.580
and caught them
in his hat.

04:49.580 --> 04:51.620
It was like a circus...
in a restaurant!

04:51.620 --> 04:53.670
[ Chuckling ]
So you'll help me?

04:53.670 --> 04:55.750
I've been sitting with you for an
hour and a half on a Thursday.

04:55.750 --> 04:57.290
I clearly have
nothing better to do.

04:57.290 --> 04:59.540
[ Laughs ]

04:59.540 --> 05:01.750
♪♪

05:01.750 --> 05:04.000
What's with all the fruits
and the leafy-green vegetables?

05:04.000 --> 05:05.290
Where is
my diet soda?

05:05.290 --> 05:06.960
That stuff's
terrible for you.

05:06.960 --> 05:08.210
It's loaded
with chemicals.

05:08.210 --> 05:10.580
70% of my portfolio's
chemicals --

05:10.580 --> 05:13.210
why shouldn't 70%
of my body be, as well?

05:13.210 --> 05:15.580
70% of your portfolio?

05:15.580 --> 05:17.170
Interesting.

05:18.710 --> 05:20.290
What are you doing?

05:20.290 --> 05:21.790
I need to do
a report for school

05:21.790 --> 05:23.290
about a successful person
in my life,

05:23.290 --> 05:24.790
and I'm choosing you.

05:24.790 --> 05:26.380
Oh. So let's start
from the beginning --

05:26.380 --> 05:28.580
what drove you to become
the man you are today?

05:28.580 --> 05:30.290
Well, I guess
it was my dad.

05:30.290 --> 05:32.460
He shined shoes
in Grand Central Station.

05:32.460 --> 05:34.880
My drive
is not to struggle like he did.

05:34.880 --> 05:37.040
You know that saying,
"Money can't buy you happiness"?

05:37.040 --> 05:38.210
[ Chuckles ] Yeah?

05:38.210 --> 05:39.750
Well,
it's nonsense.

05:39.750 --> 05:41.290
Written by
a rich person

05:41.290 --> 05:44.210
to make poor people feel better
about their sad lives.

05:44.210 --> 05:46.080
Rich people
are the best.

05:46.080 --> 05:47.420
[ Laughs ]

05:47.420 --> 05:49.250
I want to do better
than my dad, too.

05:49.250 --> 05:51.170
Well, doesn't your dad
have a book coming out?

05:51.170 --> 05:52.210
Yeah, today.

05:52.210 --> 05:54.500
Well, he can make some dollars
off of that.

05:54.500 --> 05:56.750
It's called "John Stuart Mill
and the Consequences

05:56.750 --> 05:58.670
of a Thoroughgoing
Empiricist Outlook."

05:58.670 --> 05:59.790
Oh. Well...

05:59.790 --> 06:02.080
money can't
buy you happiness.

06:02.080 --> 06:03.580
♪♪

06:03.580 --> 06:04.380
Katie!

06:04.380 --> 06:05.880
Yeah?

06:05.880 --> 06:07.750
The first reviews of my book
are in and they love it!

06:07.750 --> 06:09.580
Amazing!
Listen to this!

06:09.580 --> 06:11.380
"This isn't just
the best

06:11.380 --> 06:13.420
John Stuart Mill book
I've ever read --

06:13.420 --> 06:15.670
it's the best book
I've ever read, period."

06:15.670 --> 06:18.210
Wow.
Here's another.

06:18.210 --> 06:20.460
"Greg Otto is clearly
a gifted author and historian.

06:20.460 --> 06:22.040
And what a handsome
author photo."

06:22.040 --> 06:23.290
Well,
thank you...

06:23.290 --> 06:24.790
DragonLady853.

06:24.790 --> 06:27.750
I told you
that you were overreacting.

06:27.750 --> 06:29.460
They go on and on.
See?

06:29.460 --> 06:31.330
You were worried
about nothing.

06:31.330 --> 06:33.750
Who knows,
maybe somewhere down the road,

06:33.750 --> 06:34.920
a John Stuart Mill
musical.

06:34.920 --> 06:36.500
You're right.

06:36.500 --> 06:39.380
"Mill" is so much easier
to rhyme than "Hamilton."

06:39.380 --> 06:40.790
Will. Kill. Chill.

06:40.790 --> 06:42.210
Look at this,
I'm writing already!

06:42.210 --> 06:44.000
And we'll get your car
all fixed up.

06:44.000 --> 06:45.670
You know what?
I'm taking it in the shop today.

06:45.670 --> 06:47.000
And I'm springin'
for a gas cap.

06:47.000 --> 06:49.330
Say goodbye,
wad of balled-up paper towels.

06:49.330 --> 06:50.920
[ Laughs ]

06:50.920 --> 06:53.750
Katie: Thank you, DragonLady853
and WifeStealaForeva.

06:53.750 --> 06:55.210
Oh, my God!

06:55.210 --> 06:56.580
You are not
going to believe this --

06:56.580 --> 06:58.580
Londyn told Summit
who told Zola

06:58.580 --> 07:01.580
that Trip Windsor is going to
ask me to the winter dance.

07:01.580 --> 07:03.920
Who? He's the gorgeous
new guy at school.

07:03.920 --> 07:05.580
Nobody knows anything
about him.

07:05.580 --> 07:06.880
He's totally mysterious.

07:06.880 --> 07:08.460
Perfect.
Mysterious stranger --

07:08.460 --> 07:09.580
every mother's dream.

07:09.580 --> 07:11.080
What,
were there no drifters

07:11.080 --> 07:12.580
who kept to themselves
available?

07:12.580 --> 07:14.170
Dad. He could be a great guy.

07:14.170 --> 07:16.170
Impossible!
His name is Trip?

07:16.170 --> 07:17.830
The most slappable name
in the world.

07:17.830 --> 07:19.380
Now who's assuming
the worst?

07:19.380 --> 07:21.330
Sometimes you need to take
the leap and see what happens.

07:21.330 --> 07:23.290
Like I did with my book,
and [Chuckles]...

07:23.290 --> 07:26.830
I say go for it.
Thanks, Dad.

07:26.830 --> 07:29.000
You're not going to any dance
with a boy that we haven't met!

07:29.000 --> 07:32.460
Katie, jump and the net will appear.
[ Groans ]

07:32.460 --> 07:36.670
Damn you, DragonLady853
and WifeStealaForeva!

07:36.670 --> 07:38.790
♪♪

07:38.790 --> 07:40.790
Anna-Kat: Stay.

07:40.790 --> 07:41.750
[ Hans Gruber oinking ]

07:41.750 --> 07:42.790
Stay.

07:42.790 --> 07:44.250
Stay!

07:44.250 --> 07:47.000
Please, Hans Gruber!
You have to hide!

07:47.000 --> 07:48.170
[ Sighs ]

07:48.170 --> 07:50.380
You need to understand --

07:50.380 --> 07:53.080
you've lived
a very sheltered life.

07:53.080 --> 07:56.540
But now people you've loved
and trusted want to eat you.

07:56.540 --> 07:57.710
[ Hans Gruber squealing ]

07:57.710 --> 07:59.290
Why did you have to be
so delicious?

07:59.290 --> 08:00.580
[ Hans Gruber oinking ]

08:00.580 --> 08:02.000
Okay...

08:02.000 --> 08:04.500
when I turn back around,
you better be gone.

08:04.500 --> 08:05.620
[ Exhales deeply ]

08:05.620 --> 08:07.290
1...

08:07.290 --> 08:08.710
2...

08:08.710 --> 08:11.210
3!

08:11.210 --> 08:12.500
Where was this obedience

08:12.500 --> 08:15.000
when I told you
to stop pooping in my closet?

08:16.210 --> 08:19.330
Hans Gruber...

08:19.330 --> 08:21.880
you can't fall asleep without
your lavender night mask!

08:21.880 --> 08:23.880
♪♪

08:23.880 --> 08:25.460
Sounds like
the reviews worked.

08:25.460 --> 08:27.710
Two days later, and he's out
getting the car fixed.

08:27.710 --> 08:29.540
Yeah, but I think you guys
might've gone too far.

08:29.540 --> 08:31.920
There's a subtle shift in Greg
ever since he read them.

08:31.920 --> 08:34.380
He encouraged Taylor
to hang out with Trip,

08:34.380 --> 08:36.790
and he's been doing finger guns
quite a bit lately.

08:36.790 --> 08:37.880
Is that so bad?

08:40.290 --> 08:41.960
That's horrible!
I am so sorry!

08:41.960 --> 08:44.040
But he'll snap back
when his book doesn't sell.

08:44.040 --> 08:46.120
But then you'll have
a depressed Greg on your hands.

08:46.120 --> 08:48.000
That I know
how to handle.

08:48.000 --> 08:50.250
I make him a meatloaf,
let him call me Martha,

08:50.250 --> 08:51.790
and we play
a little game called

08:51.790 --> 08:54.500
"General Washington comes home
from the war."

08:54.500 --> 08:55.880
Please don't tell me
you have a costume.

08:57.120 --> 08:58.880
You have a costume.

08:58.880 --> 08:59.880
[ Car horn honks ]

08:59.880 --> 09:01.960
Wow.
He got the horn fixed.

09:01.960 --> 09:04.000
That was fast.

09:06.380 --> 09:07.790
[ Scoffs ]

09:07.790 --> 09:09.580
That is not
your car.

09:09.580 --> 09:12.620
♪♪

09:15.330 --> 09:18.880
Well, ladies,
what do you think?

09:18.880 --> 09:21.040
You bought
a brand-new car?

09:21.040 --> 09:22.040
I got
a great deal.

09:22.040 --> 09:23.250
The dealership
gave me

09:23.250 --> 09:25.040
a month
of satellite radio for free!

09:25.040 --> 09:26.290
We can't afford
a new car.

09:26.290 --> 09:28.040
We can't afford
a new anything.

09:28.040 --> 09:29.790
The net
has appeared.

09:31.210 --> 09:33.290
It's even worse
when he does it.

09:33.290 --> 09:35.620
[ Blowing ]

09:35.620 --> 09:37.920
Oh, my God,
he holstered them.

09:42.000 --> 09:43.330
What is this?

09:43.330 --> 09:45.210
You were supposed to
get your car fixed.

09:45.210 --> 09:47.210
I was, until I pulled into
the shop at the dealership

09:47.210 --> 09:48.750
and I saw this baby
in the window.

09:48.750 --> 09:50.670
Sometimes you just have to say,
"What the heck?"

09:50.670 --> 09:52.000
Mm.

09:52.000 --> 09:53.290
Then I stopped at Benihana
for lunch.

09:53.290 --> 09:54.710
It's not as fun when it's just you.
Greg.

09:54.710 --> 09:56.250
This is a new car.

09:56.250 --> 09:58.170
We're not
a new-car family.

09:58.170 --> 10:00.290
We're not
a new-anything family.

10:00.290 --> 10:02.790
You know why our pillowcases
are so soft?

10:02.790 --> 10:05.380
I bought them
at the Petersons' yard sale.

10:05.380 --> 10:08.750
That's right, we sleep on
dead-people sheets.

10:08.750 --> 10:10.920
I knew you'd be a bit hesitant. Let
me show you what this baby's got.

10:10.920 --> 10:11.920
[ Groans ]

10:11.920 --> 10:13.620
Front-wheel drive.

10:13.620 --> 10:15.210
Heated front seats.

10:15.210 --> 10:16.790
Intelligent
clearance sonar.

10:16.790 --> 10:18.120
Ask me
what that means?

10:18.120 --> 10:20.040
I don't know,
but it's awesome!

10:20.040 --> 10:21.170
Does that
have any features

10:21.170 --> 10:22.420
that let you
go back in time and return it?

10:22.420 --> 10:25.210
I know my cheap Greg
is in there somewhere.

10:25.210 --> 10:26.790
The one
who waters down Palmolive

10:26.790 --> 10:28.500
so I can barely
get my dishes clean.

10:28.500 --> 10:30.040
What are you
talking about?

10:30.040 --> 10:32.420
This car
needs to go back.

10:32.420 --> 10:34.000
Katie,
we're fine.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.170
The reviews for my book
are amazing.

10:36.170 --> 10:37.620
It'll be a hit --
I'll get tenure.

10:37.620 --> 10:39.330
We deserve to be
a new-car family.

10:39.330 --> 10:41.250
Your book
only has two reviews.

10:41.250 --> 10:43.540
Two stellar reviews.

10:43.540 --> 10:44.960
Yeah.

10:44.960 --> 10:46.880
"This isn't a book --
it's a revelation.

10:46.880 --> 10:49.380
This love letter to Mill
is a masterpiece

10:49.380 --> 10:51.250
our generation
doesn't deserve."

10:51.250 --> 10:52.250
That...

10:52.250 --> 10:53.790
is an excellent
turn of phrase.

10:53.790 --> 10:55.170
There's another one.

10:55.170 --> 10:56.580
"This treatise
has no equal.

10:56.580 --> 11:00.000
It is the sun and we are
fortunate to bask in its light.

11:00.000 --> 11:01.790
Greg Otto is a luminary."

11:01.790 --> 11:04.080
But reviews
are not sales.

11:04.080 --> 11:05.880
A luminary, Katie.

11:05.880 --> 11:07.380
[ Engine revving ]

11:07.380 --> 11:10.460
[ Brakes squeal ]

11:10.460 --> 11:13.670
Whoa, Taylor's really
stepped up her game.

11:13.670 --> 11:15.000
Hey, guys.

11:15.000 --> 11:17.880
This is Trip -- my non-drifter
date to the dance.

11:17.880 --> 11:19.880
Whoa!

11:19.880 --> 11:21.710
Sweet ride.

11:21.710 --> 11:24.420
Love this guy.
See? Who was right?

11:24.420 --> 11:26.080
Is there anything
I'm not nailin' today?

11:26.080 --> 11:27.420
Yeah,
I can think of something.

11:27.420 --> 11:29.460
So, is that
your car?

11:29.460 --> 11:31.580
Yeah. Yep. My parents promised to
buy the car if I got straight C's.

11:31.580 --> 11:32.830
Ahh.

11:32.830 --> 11:34.080
Straight C's?

11:34.080 --> 11:35.420
Yeah.
And I finally got 'em.

11:35.420 --> 11:36.710
Mm.

11:36.710 --> 11:38.960
Well, one D,
but it was just English,

11:38.960 --> 11:40.380
so my parents
were cool.

11:40.380 --> 11:41.880
What kinda mileage
you get on that thing?

11:41.880 --> 11:43.170
Uhhh...

11:43.170 --> 11:44.580
If this is
a test,

11:44.580 --> 11:46.170
I'm legally allowed
to take it untimed.

11:46.170 --> 11:47.830
[ Groans ]

11:47.830 --> 11:49.250
Whoa!

11:49.250 --> 11:51.420
This thing's got
so many buttons.

11:51.420 --> 11:52.920
Yeah, it does.
High five!

11:52.920 --> 11:54.170
Red sports-car club!

11:54.170 --> 11:55.500
Yeah.
[ Chuckles ]

11:55.500 --> 11:57.000
Great.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.620
Now I'm dealing with a smart
moron and a moron moron.

11:59.620 --> 12:01.040
Hans Gruber?

12:01.040 --> 12:03.540
Where have you gone to?

12:03.540 --> 12:07.080
I've got your favorite food --
trash.

12:07.080 --> 12:09.040
♪♪

12:09.040 --> 12:10.880
[ Laughter ]

12:10.880 --> 12:11.960
This is
all your fault.

12:11.960 --> 12:13.880
Our fault?
Yes!

12:13.880 --> 12:15.580
Your reviews
were too good.

12:15.580 --> 12:18.380
And now Greg is spending money
we don't have.

12:18.380 --> 12:20.000
Hey, don't hand Michelangelo
a paint brush

12:20.000 --> 12:22.080
and then complain
when you get the Sistine Chapel.

12:22.080 --> 12:24.210
I got them to throw in
a free month of satellite radio,

12:24.210 --> 12:26.040
and this month
has 31 days, so...

12:26.040 --> 12:27.080
Legend!

12:27.080 --> 12:28.290
[ Laughter ]

12:28.290 --> 12:30.670
I've got to
tell Greg the truth.

12:30.670 --> 12:32.210
That you had us
make up reviews

12:32.210 --> 12:34.290
so he could feel good and
you could get your car fixed?

12:34.290 --> 12:36.120
God,
that's the truth?

12:36.120 --> 12:37.790
The truth
sounds awful.

12:37.790 --> 12:40.790
Greg, can I have a word
with you?

12:40.790 --> 12:43.080
Kind of in the middle of
a red-sports-car club meeting.

12:43.080 --> 12:44.380
Come on, Trip,
let's go.

12:44.380 --> 12:45.750
Whenever my mom
says that,

12:45.750 --> 12:47.790
it's never one word,
and it's never good.

12:47.790 --> 12:49.250
Meeting adjourned.

12:49.250 --> 12:51.540
Love it.

12:53.120 --> 12:55.500
About the reviews
you got --

12:55.500 --> 12:57.330
Yeah, I still can't believe them.
Good.

12:57.330 --> 12:59.000
That is a good zone
to be in,

12:59.000 --> 13:00.460
but the thing is --
[ Ringtone plays ]

13:00.460 --> 13:02.830
Whoa! It's my publisher.
Talk to me, Vance.

13:02.830 --> 13:04.580
Thank God.
I'm off the hook.

13:04.580 --> 13:06.580
His publisher will tell him
the book bombed,

13:06.580 --> 13:08.250
and I'll be here
to cheer him up

13:08.250 --> 13:10.120
dressed as a panty-less
Martha Washington.

13:10.120 --> 13:12.120
Then we can return the car
and go back to normal.

13:13.170 --> 13:16.670
Oh, Greg,
I'm sorry.

13:16.670 --> 13:19.540
The book sold out.
All 10,000 copies.

13:19.540 --> 13:20.540
It's a hit!

13:20.540 --> 13:23.000
Yeah,
I'd be speechless, too,

13:23.000 --> 13:25.620
if I found myself
married to a luminary.

13:25.620 --> 13:27.170
Sorry, "moist."

13:27.170 --> 13:30.170
"Luminary" just became
my new least-favorite word.

13:30.170 --> 13:33.170
♪♪

13:33.170 --> 13:35.170
A best-seller
and a new car?

13:35.170 --> 13:37.000
Sounds like
your dad's on a roll.

13:37.000 --> 13:40.000
I won't be offended if you want
to write that report on him.

13:40.000 --> 13:41.960
Why would I write about him
when I can write about you?

13:41.960 --> 13:43.380
Your life's amazing.

13:43.380 --> 13:45.080
You were the one

13:45.080 --> 13:46.790
who turned Michael Jackson on
to chimpanzees.

13:46.790 --> 13:49.380
Anyone can write about me.
Hell, plenty of people have.

13:49.380 --> 13:51.670
But no one has yet broken
the story of Greg Otto.

13:51.670 --> 13:53.080
I guess.

13:53.080 --> 13:55.170
But my dad's never even
been to prison.

13:55.170 --> 13:56.250
And I don't
want you to keep

13:56.250 --> 13:57.880
building up federal prison
in your head.

13:57.880 --> 13:59.000
I mean,
it's great,

13:59.000 --> 14:01.290
but to put it in terms
you'd understand --

14:01.290 --> 14:06.290
Oahu, Lanai, Maui,
prison, Kauai.

14:06.290 --> 14:10.460
♪♪

14:10.460 --> 14:12.460
It's true.
It's sold out.

14:12.460 --> 14:13.710
I know.

14:13.710 --> 14:14.750
Greg is so happy.

14:14.750 --> 14:16.210
It's like that time
he thought

14:16.210 --> 14:17.880
he saw Bill Nye
at the farmers market.

14:17.880 --> 14:19.500
Hello.

14:19.500 --> 14:21.540
Hmm...

14:21.540 --> 14:24.500
Do we have
any tapenade?

14:24.500 --> 14:27.920
I don't think so because
I don't know what that is.

14:27.920 --> 14:29.000
Well, we're gonna need
to get some

14:29.000 --> 14:30.580
because now that
I'm a celebrated author,

14:30.580 --> 14:32.580
I'm gonna start hosting
a weekly salon

14:32.580 --> 14:34.250
here at the house.

14:34.250 --> 14:36.500
Why would we get haircuts
in our house?

14:36.500 --> 14:38.710
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, Katie. No.

14:38.710 --> 14:42.040
A salon is a gathering of minds
to explore intellectual topics.

14:43.290 --> 14:46.120
I'm not loving
what's going on here.

14:46.120 --> 14:48.040
You ladies are welcome
to come to the salon,

14:48.040 --> 14:49.330
as observers,
of course.

14:49.330 --> 14:52.000
You can observe me
giving you one of these.

14:52.000 --> 14:53.750
Greg:
[ Chuckles ] Okay.

14:53.750 --> 14:55.210
I know you're not happy
with where you are in life,

14:55.210 --> 14:57.460
but someday, girls,
like me,

14:57.460 --> 14:59.460
your ship will come in.

14:59.460 --> 15:02.540
Uh, I only have my kids
every other weekend.

15:02.540 --> 15:04.710
My ship
has come in, baby.

15:04.710 --> 15:05.500
[ Chuckles ]

15:05.500 --> 15:08.000
♪♪

15:08.000 --> 15:10.880
You know, sometimes I think
your Second Breakfast rants

15:10.880 --> 15:13.540
are just you complaining,
but this [bleep] is real.

15:13.540 --> 15:15.920
[ Laughs ]

15:15.920 --> 15:18.040
See you at school.

15:21.420 --> 15:24.170
Hey, Kate, can you tell Greg
that I had to scoot?

15:27.330 --> 15:29.330
Mrs. Otto
will tell Mr. Otto

15:29.330 --> 15:32.080
that Taylor's new friend
had to leave.

15:32.080 --> 15:33.330
Yeah,
you can tell him, too.

15:33.330 --> 15:35.380
Whatever.
Trip...

15:35.380 --> 15:37.710
I don't think
you and Taylor should date.

15:37.710 --> 15:39.000
Totally!

15:39.000 --> 15:40.460
We're on
the same page.

15:40.460 --> 15:41.500
Keeping it caj.

15:41.500 --> 15:43.540
Just a fun, physical thing,
you know?

15:43.540 --> 15:45.420
Lates, Kate.

15:45.420 --> 15:46.540
[ Sighs ]

15:46.540 --> 15:48.750
Easy on the eyes.
Tough on the brain.

15:48.750 --> 15:50.000
Bright side --

15:50.000 --> 15:52.000
Taylor gets to be the smart one
in the relationship.

15:52.000 --> 15:53.330
Ugh!

15:53.330 --> 15:55.000
Greg and Taylor
are stressing me out!

15:55.000 --> 15:56.330
I'm going to go sit
in the new Camry

15:56.330 --> 15:57.960
and enjoy
that there are no sticky pennies

15:57.960 --> 16:00.080
stuck in
the cup holders.

16:00.080 --> 16:01.750
[ Both chuckle ]

16:05.420 --> 16:06.750
[ Grunts ]

16:06.750 --> 16:08.920
[ Hans Gruber squeals ]

16:08.920 --> 16:10.420
Hans Gruber!

16:10.420 --> 16:12.960
[ Hans Gruber squeals ]

16:12.960 --> 16:17.120
Ohh, hey, bacon legs,
get back here!

16:17.120 --> 16:19.540
[ Hans Gruber squeals ]

16:19.540 --> 16:22.580
Ohh!

16:22.580 --> 16:27.750
♪♪

16:27.750 --> 16:31.500
[ Dramatic music plays ]

16:31.500 --> 16:33.380
I don't know
what the pig told you,

16:33.380 --> 16:34.500
but they're not mine.

16:34.500 --> 16:35.920
♪♪

16:40.120 --> 16:42.580
How many of Greg's books
did you buy?

16:42.580 --> 16:43.790
All of them.

16:43.790 --> 16:45.040
Why?

16:45.040 --> 16:46.750
Well,
Oliver was interviewing me

16:46.750 --> 16:48.920
for a report on
someone successful in his life,

16:48.920 --> 16:50.040
and I thought he should do it
on his dad

16:50.040 --> 16:51.580
instead of me.

16:51.580 --> 16:53.750
So you bought the books
to make Greg look good.

16:53.750 --> 16:55.330
Well, a boy should be
proud of his father.

16:55.330 --> 16:57.420
I wasn't,
and I regret it.

16:57.420 --> 16:59.710
That's very sweet of you,
Spencer.

16:59.710 --> 17:01.620
But 10,000 copies?

17:01.620 --> 17:04.380
I only meant to buy a few dozen,
but when I did --

17:04.380 --> 17:06.830
Have you seen
this amazon.com thing?

17:06.830 --> 17:08.380
Of course!

17:08.380 --> 17:10.250
You haven't lived
until you get a snow shovel

17:10.250 --> 17:12.080
and baby carrots
in the same package.

17:12.080 --> 17:13.580
I'm banned
from trading stocks,

17:13.580 --> 17:15.210
so when I started
buying Greg's book

17:15.210 --> 17:17.420
and I saw it
climb up the sales ranking,

17:17.420 --> 17:19.420
it gave me a rush
like the old days.

17:19.420 --> 17:20.920
And before I knew it,
I bought them all.

17:20.920 --> 17:23.420
Come on,
Hans Gruber.

17:23.420 --> 17:26.290
Let's go home and bring
our luminary back down to Earth.

17:26.290 --> 17:29.290
What are you going to do
with all these books?

17:29.290 --> 17:31.830
Disappoint trick-or-treaters
for the next 10 or so years.

17:31.830 --> 17:34.880
♪♪

17:34.880 --> 17:37.420
Greg, I need to talk to you
about something.

17:37.420 --> 17:39.170
[ Gasps ]
Hans Gruber, you're safe,

17:39.170 --> 17:40.670
and you don't have to hide
anymore!

17:40.670 --> 17:42.170
My dad's book
is a success,

17:42.170 --> 17:44.080
so we can afford
not to eat you!

17:44.080 --> 17:45.250
Well, Hans,
don't get too comfortable.

17:46.540 --> 17:48.210
Greg, I need
to tell you s--

17:48.210 --> 17:49.790
"Until this report,
I never knew

17:49.790 --> 17:50.960
that my dad
wrote his book at night

17:50.960 --> 17:52.540
after we all
went to sleep.

17:52.540 --> 17:54.380
Sometimes he worked
until 4:00 in the morning

17:54.380 --> 17:56.080
because he put
his family first.

17:56.080 --> 17:58.080
He didn't sacrifice us
for his dream.

17:58.080 --> 18:01.120
And still,
his dream came true.

18:01.120 --> 18:03.000
Sometimes being
a good man

18:03.000 --> 18:05.040
makes you
a great man.

18:05.040 --> 18:07.250
I couldn't be more proud
to be his son."

18:08.580 --> 18:10.750
That's the best review
I've ever gotten.

18:10.750 --> 18:13.380
♪♪

18:14.710 --> 18:17.170
I'm gonna put
a cover on this

18:17.170 --> 18:18.290
and go watch
"Game of Thrones."

18:18.290 --> 18:19.330
No,
you're not.

18:19.330 --> 18:20.540
All my friends
are allowed to.

18:20.540 --> 18:21.540
No,
they're not.

18:24.540 --> 18:25.580
Mm.

18:25.580 --> 18:26.790
I'm proud
of you, too.

18:26.790 --> 18:28.040
Thanks, honey.

18:28.040 --> 18:29.250
What did you
want to talk about?

18:29.250 --> 18:31.210
Just, um...

18:31.210 --> 18:34.830
What should we serve
at your salon?

18:34.830 --> 18:36.790
Hmm...

18:36.790 --> 18:38.920
pistachios.

18:38.920 --> 18:40.620
Pistachios?

18:40.620 --> 18:43.920
Oh, God, I so want to tell him
about the books!

18:43.920 --> 18:45.960
♪♪

18:45.960 --> 18:48.460
Hey, Mom.
Trip's gonna pick me up.

18:48.460 --> 18:50.540
We're gonna go see a movie.
Taylor.

18:50.540 --> 18:51.620
Sit down.

18:51.620 --> 18:52.830
Here it comes.

18:52.830 --> 18:54.580
Here what comes?

18:54.580 --> 18:56.000
You don't like him.
You don't want me seeing him.

18:56.000 --> 18:56.920
You think
I'm too good for him.

18:56.920 --> 18:58.210
That's the gist
of it,

18:58.210 --> 18:59.290
but I would have
said it snarkier.

18:59.290 --> 19:01.920
I still want to date him. Why?

19:01.920 --> 19:04.250
Because he's nice.
And he's cute. [ Chuckles ]

19:04.250 --> 19:06.330
And you always talk about
all the dumb guys

19:06.330 --> 19:07.620
you dated
before Dad.

19:07.620 --> 19:09.670
Maybe the reason
you fell in love with him

19:09.670 --> 19:12.250
is because you got all those
dumb guys out of your system.

19:12.250 --> 19:13.420
No.

19:13.420 --> 19:16.250
Don't you make me see things
in a new light.

19:16.250 --> 19:17.920
I promise
I won't be home late.

19:17.920 --> 19:19.750
All right.

19:19.750 --> 19:21.920
Go to the movies.

19:21.920 --> 19:23.580
Just nothing 3-D.

19:23.580 --> 19:25.710
You don't want him doing this
the whole time.

19:25.710 --> 19:29.080
[ Chuckles ]

19:29.080 --> 19:33.540
♪♪

19:33.540 --> 19:35.750
I was thinking Wednesday
for your salon.

19:35.750 --> 19:37.580
I'll have
the tapenade ready.

19:37.580 --> 19:39.000
I looked it up online.

19:39.000 --> 19:42.210
Turns out it's just a fancy word
for mushed-up olives.

19:42.210 --> 19:43.710
I know that Spencer
bought all my books.

19:43.710 --> 19:46.170
And I know you know.

19:46.170 --> 19:48.120
I wanted
to do a book tour.

19:48.120 --> 19:50.000
So my publisher
tracked my sales

19:50.000 --> 19:51.790
to see which cities
I should visit.

19:51.790 --> 19:54.540
Turns out all my books sold
in just one town --

19:54.540 --> 19:58.290
just this town --
just one address.

19:58.290 --> 20:00.710
Spencer's.

20:00.710 --> 20:03.250
He just assumed I was there because
you'd already told me everything.

20:03.250 --> 20:05.380
He gave me a signed copy
of my own book.

20:05.380 --> 20:07.170
I don't know
why he signed it.

20:07.170 --> 20:08.790
So, thanks.

20:08.790 --> 20:10.000
For what?

20:11.290 --> 20:13.920
For knowing the truth
but letting me have the win,

20:13.920 --> 20:16.250
even though I was acting
like a pompous jerk.

20:16.250 --> 20:18.540
You weren't pompous,
honey.

20:18.540 --> 20:21.170
You were just a luminary
planning a salon.

20:21.170 --> 20:22.290
Oh, God.

20:22.290 --> 20:23.330
[ Chuckles ]

20:23.330 --> 20:25.120
I guess I let success
get to my head.

20:25.120 --> 20:26.920
Well, that won't be
a problem now.

20:26.920 --> 20:29.040
Only one person bought my book.
Hey!

20:29.040 --> 20:30.790
Who knows how many books
you might have sold

20:30.790 --> 20:32.460
if Spencer
hadn't bought them all?

20:32.460 --> 20:33.710
Yeah, I guess.

20:33.710 --> 20:37.000
Plus, as far as
the tenure committee knows,

20:37.000 --> 20:38.330
you sold 10,000 books!

20:38.330 --> 20:40.080
Don't do that thing

20:40.080 --> 20:42.460
where you tell people the truth
when you don't have to.

20:42.460 --> 20:44.380
You don't bring
the empty candy wrappers

20:44.380 --> 20:45.790
to the cash register.

20:45.790 --> 20:47.830
You tuck them behind
some produce.

20:47.830 --> 20:50.040
Katie, ethically,
I feel I have to tell them --

20:50.040 --> 20:51.830
That's the only way
we get to keep the car.

20:51.830 --> 20:53.580
That my book sold out
on the first day.

20:53.580 --> 20:56.500
♪♪

21:01.040 --> 21:02.170
You wouldn't believe
the day I had, honey.

21:02.170 --> 21:03.960
But it was worth it.
We won.

21:03.960 --> 21:06.710
So the British surrendered?

21:06.710 --> 21:07.960
Yes, verily.

21:07.960 --> 21:09.120
We surprised them
at Yorktown

21:09.120 --> 21:10.290
and battled them
back to the ocean.

21:10.290 --> 21:12.250
That's wonderful,
George.

21:12.250 --> 21:15.290
Now eat some meat loaf
and then we'll retire upstairs.

21:15.290 --> 21:16.790
[ Chuckles ]

21:16.790 --> 21:18.290
Eat fast.
The kids' movie ends at 9:00.

21:18.290 --> 21:19.290
Mmm!

21:19.290 --> 21:20.250
Yeah.
